          <div class="fn-by">Theodore Grimes, Founder</div>
        </div>

        <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

        <p>Botox and filler marketing fails not because the ads are bad or the channel is wrong, but because the consult-booking system underneath leaks. The patients are there. They are reading your reviews, scanning your before-and-afters, and reaching out. The med spas that win are not the ones with the cleverest campaigns. They are the ones that respond in 5 minutes, prove they can deliver, make booking effortless, and then keep the patient coming back.</p>

        <p>Fix speed-to-lead first. Stack reviews and real proof second. Make booking frictionless third. Do those three and the marketing you already run starts booking the consults it was always supposed to.</p>

        <h2>FAQ: Botox & Filler Marketing</h2>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is the best marketing channel for booking botox consults?</summary>
          <p>There is no single best channel. The data shows the bottleneck is rarely the channel and almost always the follow-up. 78% of customers book with the first business that responds, and responding within 5 minutes makes you about 21 times more likely to qualify a lead than responding at 30 minutes. A med spa with a mediocre channel and instant, consistent follow-up will book more consults than one with great ads and a slow front desk. Fix speed-to-lead first, then optimize the channel mix.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Why are my botox ads getting leads but not booked consults?</summary>
          <p>Almost always a follow-up gap. Most aesthetic clinics are leaving revenue on the table due to slow response times. The biggest reason leads do not convert is how long it takes to reply. Every hour of delay drops the odds sharply. The leads are fine. The system that catches them is leaking. Add an instant automated response, a friction-free booking link, and a short nurture sequence and the same leads start booking.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Do before-and-after photos and reviews really book more consults?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Aesthetics is a trust purchase, and proof is what converts. 97% of consumers read reviews for local businesses and 68% of consumers will not consider a business rated below 4 stars (BrightLocal, 2026). Real before-and-after galleries (with consent) and a strong, current review profile do more to book a consult than any clever ad. They answer the only question a botox patient actually has: can this provider deliver a natural result on someone like me?</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Is social media worth it for botox marketing?</summary>
          <p>Social is worth it for trust and discovery, not for direct booking. Organic social converts at roughly 0.5% to 1.5% for most aesthetic practices, so judging it on direct bookings will always disappoint. Its real job is to be the proof a patient checks after they find you through search, reviews, or a referral. Use it to show results, personality, and credibility, then send serious interest to a booking page and a fast human response.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Should I discount botox to get more consults?</summary>
          <p>Discounting attracts price shoppers who do not return and trains your market to wait for the next deal. A better path is to compete on trust and convenience: strong reviews, real before-and-afters, transparent pricing, instant response, and easy online booking. Botox is a repeat purchase with high lifetime value, so the goal is the patient who comes back every few months, not the one chasing the lowest single-visit price. Build the system that books and keeps the repeat patient.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How fast should a med spa respond to a botox inquiry?</summary>
          <p>Within 5 minutes for the first real touch. Responding within 5 minutes makes you about 21 times more likely to qualify a lead than waiting 30 minutes, and 78% of customers go with whoever responds first. Yet most clinics take hours, and Instagram DMs often sit until the next business day. The fix is an instant automated text or call with a booking link the moment an inquiry lands, backed by a human (or AI) who can actually book during and after hours.</p>
        </details>

        <div class="blog-cta">
          <h2>Book More Botox Consults From the Marketing You Already Run</h2>
          <p>We help Miami med spas plug the leaks between inquiry and booked consult: fast-response systems, review building, and pages that convert. Month-to-month, no lock-in. Free audit shows exactly where your consults are slipping.</p>
